User-namespace remapping, and rootless Docker.

Running as non-root inside the container helps, but two deeper moves change who the container's root actually maps to on the host. Both shrink what a breakout gets you.

First, user-namespace remapping. By default, container user-I-D zero is host user-I-D zero; they share the user namespace. Remapping breaks that. The daemon maps container root to, say, host user-I-D one hundred thousand, so from the host, the container's root is a normal, unprivileged user. A breakout via a kernel bug still lands the attacker as unprivileged. You enable it in the daemon config, by setting userns-remap to default. That creates a dock-remap user, with a sub-user-I-D range, and remaps all containers into it. The trade-offs: all containers share one remap range, so there's no per-container isolation; bind mounts get fiddly, because host files owned by one hundred thousand look like root inside; and privileged mode, and sharing host process and i-p-c namespaces, become incompatible. Leave it off for dev and continuous integration; turn it on for servers running images you trust less.

Second, rootless Docker, which goes further. User-namespace remapping still needs the daemon itself to run as root. Rootless runs the entire daemon, and all containers, under your unprivileged account. You set it up once, with the rootless setup tool, then start the user service. Now there is no root daemon to compromise; a container escape only gets an attacker your own user-I-D's privileges. The trade-offs: networking is slower, using a userspace proxy; network-host mode and privileged mode are unavailable; see-group version two is required for resource limits; and there are no host firewall rules, so port publishing goes through the userspace proxy instead. Rootless is the right answer for shared dev hosts, sandboxes, and continuous-integration runners, exactly where a compromised step shouldn't mean a compromised host.
